BFA Advising

  • Q1FY22 total time - 17 hours
  • Completed task SEAS BFA Training Session (August 13) 
                                                            Stereotype "threat" and "lift"
                                                        Imposter phenomenon, don't fix the individual but your appraoch
                                                        Microaggressions
                                                        - never make assumptions, blame individuals (or school they came from)
                                                        - don't rely on steretypes (i.e.: South culture)
                                                        - false expectations of performance and  identity (asians are smarter) "you'll do fine", "everyting will work out" but instead provide straegies and resources
                                                        - students can't always reach out to advisors (you may only learn from proctor or grades)
                                                        - remind them how you are there as a resource for them
                                                        Growth mindset (leverage mistakes, risks), vs. Fixed mindset (stereotypical assumtions on race, etc.)
                                                        - avoid praising intelligence and sheer effort, instead acknowledge importance of planning and trying new approaches
                                                        - importancxe of strategies and challanges
                                                        - encourage to expand on answers, explore thought process to better prepare for their meeting with faculty, etc. (define needed assistance)
                                                        Early semester advise on scenarios such as extensions (extension policy in sylabus), falling behind when sick, at beginning of feeling of falling behind
                                                        Unconditionally support student, not bias with SEAS. Understand the "why" behind students decisions (i.e.: changing concentration, family, peers prressures)
                                                        - Support "how" to pursue goals bu not to change them
            
                                                        Open door of communication
                                                        - Not become defensive on our rensponses
                                                        - Face to face conversation to affirm student's feelings
